    "id": "vc-easy-glossy"
  }, "VC Easy Glossy"), mdx("p", null, "One afternoon I began discussing the WCAC Celadon Clear with a WCAC member, Nancy Alt.\xA0 I was very surprised to discover the interesting history of this glaze."), mdx("p", null, "In 2009 Nancy Alt had visited Val Cushing\u2019s home and purchased a vase with a lovely blue-green celadon glaze. Nancy asked Val if he could share the glaze recipe, and he not only shared it but converted it from cone 9 to cone 6 (the temperature Nancy was firing). Val\u2019s email is copied below. It shows the extremely generous nature of this amazing potter and teacher:"), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "From: Val Cushing"), mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "Subject: Re: celedon glaze"), mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "Date: May 12, 2009 at 12:46:57 PM EDT\nhero:\nexcerpt: "), mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "To: Nancy Alt"), mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "Dear Nancy,"), mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "This glaze is one I made for C/9 oxidation electric firing, so that it would appear to be a blue green celadon. I have revised it for you to be the same color and texture only for C/6 ox. electric . I will give you two to try , first VC Pale Emerald, C/6 , glossy , blue/green , celadon looking. as follows\u2026 Kona F/4 feldspar 24, Ferro Frit 3134 24, Dolomite 4, whiting 14, barium carbonate 2, zinc oxide 2, flint 24, and EPK 6. ADD TO THAT , 1/2 % COPPER CARBONATE for blue green. VC/easy glossy, C/6 ox. , electric , celadon looking , green. Cornwall Stone 46, Gerstley Borate 20, Ferro Frit 3124 26, Ball Clay 8. --- add 2% copper carb. and 1/2 % red iron oxide for celadon looking green color. Test these two Nancy and if the color is not exactly what you expected let me know and we can make a revision. We may have different \u201Ctastes\u201D about color , but we can get what you want\u2026My pale emerald should be quite a bit like the glaze on the jar of mine you now have. and THANK YOU . Val")), mdx("p", null, "So it turns out that the glaze I liked so much,\xA0WCAC Celadon Clear, was actually a Val Cushing recipe called \u201CEasy Glossy\u201D.\xA0 I checked Cushing\u2019s Handbook for the recipe and didn\u2019t find it.\xA0 Nor could I find similar recipes in the Glazy database.\xA0 So it\u2019s quite possible this is a newly discovered Val Cushing glaze recipe."), mdx("p", null, "However, the WCAC Celadon Clear had been modified from the original \u201CEasy Glossy\u201D, most notably subbing Gerstley Borate for Gillespie Borate.\xA0 I wanted to see not only the original recipe but also the color variations that Cushing was working with.\xA0 So I created a triaxial blend."), mdx("p", null, "Below is the triaxial blend using Copper Carbonate and Red Iron Oxide."), mdx("p", null, mdx("a", _extends({
